9","1215":"1215","1325":"1325","1346":"1346","1224":"1224","1245":"1245","1229":"1229","1218":"1218","Colemore, Hampshire, England":"Colemore, Hampshire, England","Buckinghamshire, England":"Buckinghamshire, England","Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom":"Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Ballard","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from Middle English <i>ballard</i> ‘bald-headed man’ (compare   Bald   3).","French: from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Balhard</i>, composed of the elements <i>bal</i>, presumably meaning ‘torment, spitefulness’, and <i>hard</i> ‘hard, strong’. Compare   Ballor  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Ballon","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Sergio, Alfonso, Cesar, Conchita, Emigdio, Enrique, Felipe, Francisco, Jose Luis, Julio, Ruben.  Jewish Hyman, Isadore.","Spanish and Galician: unexplained.","French and English (Middlesex): from the Old French personal name <i>Ballon</i>, <i>Ballun</i>, derived from the oblique stem of ancient Germanic <i>Ballo</i>, a short form of compound names based on the element <i>bal</i>, presumably meaning ‘torment, spitefulness’ (see   Ballard  )."]},{"name":"Bald","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Hans, Inge, Karl-Heinz, Konrad, Kurt, Otto.","German: from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Baldo</i>, or a short form of various compound names such as   Baldwin  , formed with the first element <i>bald</i> ‘bold, strong’.","Scottish and English: from the Norman personal name <i>Bald(e)</i>, <i>Baud(e)</i>, occasionally <i>Bold</i>, a short form of the common ancient Germanic personal names   Baldwin   or <i>Baldric</i>, or possibly a survival of Old English <i>Beald</i> (compare   Balding  ); the relevant element in each of these is <i>b(e)ald</i> ‘brave’. As a hereditary surname it seems to have died out in England but survives in Scotland."]},{"name":"Ballor","meanings":["Altered form of French   Ballard   2, reflecting the characteristic Canadian and American French rounding of the <i>-ard</i> ending. It is found mainly in MI."]},{"name":"Bollard","meanings":["English (Northamptonshire) and Irish: probably a variant of   Ballard  . According to MacLysaght, this is a surname of Dutch origin which was taken to Ireland early in the 18th century.","French: from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Bolohard</i>, composed of the elements <i>bolo</i> ‘friend, brother’ and <i>hard</i> ‘hard, strong’."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":23,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":32,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Decla